This repo presents the source data and the Fortran program bayes_mtf implementing the method of the upcoming article
B. Delley and Y.L. Delley, 
"Bayesian approach to slanted-edge modulation transfer function measurements for lens and pixel-sensor systems"
J. Opt. Soc. Am. A 43(8), 1202-1209 (2026)

bayes_mtf analyzes slanted edge image files of linear P2 type GrayMap files. The black level is implied to be zero.

some DETAILS:

Program output is with a file on std output and several
.eps graphic files that can be incorporated into a latex publication
and a edge_sfr_values.txt file, similar to mtf_mapper output as used in
B. Delley and F. van den Bergh,
"Fast full-field modulation transfer function analysis for photographic lens quality assessment",
Applied Optics. 60 (8). 2197-2206 (2021)

graphic eps output can be looked at on screen using gv like:
gv  g_MTF_OTF.eps    

running bayes_mtf can be simply like:

bayes_mtf  pix_meas_f28_meridional_A52.pgm
 
the specific input values, needed to reproduce section 5.2 of the article, are supplied and processed from the first comment line of the slanted edge image file.

The input values on the first comment line override program internal default values.
Explicit parameters given with the program call override default and comment line values.
Documentation of call arguments is given at the begin of the bayes_mtf.f source.
bayes_mtf output shows a call sequence with all parameter values that are in force.


Preparing a linear .pgm file from a Nikon uncompressed or lossless-compressed NEF file:
dcraw -D -4 -c DSC_????.NEF | pnmtoplainpnm > pix.pgm

LibRaw is the successor of dcraw and covers a wider set of cameras:
  unprocessed_raw $file | pnmtoplainpnm > pix.pgm

in the case of Nikon Z8 generate a pix_crop.pgm file iw1-iw2 ih1-ih2 with black level subtraction iblack=1008
bayes_mtf pix.pgm iw1 iw2 ih1 ih2 1008 

Find black level by
exiftool $ImageFile | grep -i black  


SETUP:

make requires gfortran. It can be installed  in Ubuntu:
 sudo apt update
 sudo apt install gfortran

viewing .eps files can be done with gv. Installation in Ubuntu:
 sudo apt install gv

netpbm may be part of the distribution, else
 sudo apt install netpbm

dcraw
 sudo apt install dcraw

libraw
 sudo apt install libraw-dev

exiftool
 sudo apt install libimage-exiftool-perl


